      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER IV: THE OPTION B TRAP</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fegli-section-title">Why Option B Becomes a <em>Problem</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">Option B (1-5 times salary) is where most federal employees get trapped. It's reasonably priced during your career but becomes outrageously expensive in retirement — precisely when your coverage needs have typically diminished.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The Option B Lifecycle</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem;">
          <div style="text-align: center; padding: 1rem;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Early Career</h4>
            <div style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); font-size: 2rem; color: #003870; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✓</div>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 0.9rem; color: #64748b;">Young family, mortgage, affordable premiums. Option B makes sense.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; padding: 1rem;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Mid-Career</h4>
            <div style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); font-size: 2rem; color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">?</div>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 0.9rem; color: #64748b;">Premiums rising, but coverage still needed. Time to evaluate alternatives.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; padding: 1rem;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Retirement</h4>
            <div style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); font-size: 2rem; color: #003870; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✗</div>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 0.9rem; color: #64748b;">Kids grown, house paid off, high premiums. Usually time to reduce or drop.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">The trap occurs because many federal employees elect high Option B coverage early in their career and never revisit the decision. They get comfortable with automatic payroll deductions and don't realize how expensive the coverage becomes in retirement.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">From the book examples: Federal employees who kept Option B into retirement often spent $50,000-$100,000 more on life insurance over their retirement years than necessary, money that could have enhanced their retirement lifestyle or been left to their heirs.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- PRIVATE ALTERNATIVES -->
    <section id="private-alternatives" class="fed-ed-fegli-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER V: ALTERNATIVES</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fegli-section-title">Private Insurance <em>Comparison</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">Private life insurance offers several advantages over FEGLI, especially for healthy federal employees. The key is getting coverage while you're still young and healthy, before health issues make you uninsurable.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <table class="fed-ed-comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Feature</th>
              <th>FEGLI</th>
              <th>Private Term Life</th>
              <th>Winner</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Medical Underwriting</strong></td>
              <td>None required</td>
              <td>Required</td>
              <td>FEGLI</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Premiums (Healthy 40-year-old)</strong></td>
              <td>$45/month</td>
              <td>$25/month</td>
              <td>Private</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Premiums (70-year-old)</strong></td>
              <td>$520/month</td>
              <td>Policy expires</td>
              <td>Private</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td><strong>Coverage Flexibility</strong></td>
              <td>Limited options</td>
              <td>Customizable</td>
              <td>Private</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Portability</strong></td>
              <td>Tied to federal employment</td>
              <td>Fully portable</td>
              <td>Private</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Conversion Options</strong></td>
              <td>Limited</td>
              <td>Good</td>
              <td>Private</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">The optimal strategy for many federal employees: Keep Basic FEGLI (it's free in retirement), replace expensive Option B with level-premium term life insurance that expires when coverage is no longer needed (typically age 65-70).</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-stats-grid">
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">50%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Potential Savings with Private Insurance</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">20</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Years Typical Term Length</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">$500k</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Common Coverage Amount</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
    
    <!-- COVERAGE NEEDS ANALYSIS -->
    <section id="coverage-needs" class="fed-ed-fegli-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VI: NEEDS ANALYSIS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fegli-section-title">How Much Coverage Do You <em>Actually</em> Need?</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">Most federal employees elect life insurance based on what's available rather than what they actually need. A proper needs analysis considers your family situation, debts, income replacement needs, and existing assets.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Coverage Needs Calculation</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem;">
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Financial Obligations</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">+ Mortgage balance</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">+ Other debts</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">+ Children's education costs</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">+ Income replacement (5-10 years)</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">+ Final expenses</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Existing Assets</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">- Emergency savings</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">- TSP account</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">- Other investments</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">- Spouse's income/benefits</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">- FERS survivor annuity</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 2rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 2px solid #F09F54;">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); font-size: 1.5rem; color: #003870;">Coverage Needed = Obligations - Assets</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">As you approach retirement, this equation typically shifts dramatically. Your mortgage gets paid down, your children become financially independent, your TSP grows, and your spouse may qualify for your FERS survivor annuity — all reducing your life insurance needs.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- OPTIMIZATION STRATEGIES -->
    <section id="optimization" class="fed-ed-fegli-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VII: OPTIMIZATION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fegli-section-title">FEGLI Optimization <em>Strategy</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">The optimal FEGLI strategy evolves throughout your career. What makes sense at age 30 with young children may be completely inappropriate at age 60 approaching retirement. Regular review and adjustment are essential.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Recommended Strategy by Life Stage</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem;">
          <div style="border-right: 1px solid #f3f4f6; padding-right: 2rem;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Early Career (20s-30s)</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; font-size: 0.9rem;">
              <li>Keep Basic FEGLI</li>
              <li>Consider moderate Option B</li>
              <li>Compare with private term life</li>
              <li>Option C for family coverage</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div style="border-right: 1px solid #f3f4f6; padding-right: 2rem;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Mid-Career (40s-50s)</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; font-size: 0.9rem;">
              <li>Review Option B costs vs. needs</li>
              <li>Consider private insurance while healthy</li>
              <li>Plan reduction strategy for retirement</li>
              <li>Evaluate spousal coverage needs</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Pre-Retirement (55+)</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; font-size: 0.9rem;">
              <li>Significantly reduce Option B</li>
              <li>Keep Basic FEGLI (free in retirement)</li>
              <li>Consider final expenses coverage only</li>
              <li>Plan for survivor benefit coordination</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">The key insight: FEGLI is designed for convenience, not optimization. Most federal employees benefit from a hybrid approach — using FEGLI strategically while supplementing with private coverage when appropriate.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">Our analysis typically finds federal employees can save $2,000-$5,000 annually by optimizing their life insurance strategy, while often maintaining better coverage for their actual needs.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</section>

<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section class="fed-ed-faq">
  <div class="fed-ed-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VIII: COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fegli-section-title">FEGLI Planning <em>FAQ</em></h2>
      <p class="fed-ed-fegli-body">Everything you need to know about federal life insurance and private alternatives.</p>
      <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/contact/" class="fed-ed-btn-primary">Analyze My Coverage</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="fed-ed-faq-accordion">
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">How much does FEGLI cost in retirement?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">Basic FEGLI reduces by 75% in retirement but remains free (no premium). Optional coverages are where costs can become problematic. Option A continues at $10,000 of coverage, and premiums increase with age. Option B (1-5 times salary) continues at full value, but premiums increase dramatically — often several hundred dollars per month for older retirees. Option C (family coverage) also continues with age-based premium increases. The key issue: while coverage continues, you're paying much higher rates in retirement when you may no longer need the same coverage level you had during your working years.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Should I keep FEGLI or get private insurance?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">It depends on your health, age, and coverage needs. FEGLI's advantages: no medical underwriting, guaranteed issue, and convenience. Private insurance advantages: often lower premiums (especially for healthy individuals), fixed-term coverage that ends when you no longer need it, and potentially larger death benefits. Many federal employees benefit from keeping Basic FEGLI (it's free in retirement anyway) while replacing expensive Option B coverage with a lower-cost private term policy. We recommend getting a private insurance quote to compare — if you're healthy, you may be paying far more than necessary.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">What is Option B and why is it expensive?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">Option B is additional life insurance coverage equal to 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 times your annual salary. During your working years, it's relatively affordable. The problem arises in retirement: Option B continues at full value (based on your salary at retirement), but premiums are based on your age and increase every 5 years. For a 70-year-old retiree with high Option B coverage, premiums can exceed $500-800 per month. By that age, many retirees no longer have the same coverage needs (mortgage paid off, kids financially independent), making these premiums difficult to justify.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Can I get private life insurance instead of FEGLI?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">Yes. You're not required to keep FEGLI, and you can cancel optional coverages at any time (though you may not be able to re-enroll later without a life event). Many federal employees choose to keep Basic FEGLI since it's free in retirement, but replace costly Option B with a private term life insurance policy that ends when coverage is no longer needed. Private insurance requires medical underwriting, so your health, age, and lifestyle affect eligibility and pricing. We can help you compare options and determine if private coverage makes sense for your situation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">When should I review my FEGLI coverage?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">You should review FEGLI at major life events: marriage, divorce, birth of children, home purchase, mortgage payoff, and as you approach retirement (ideally 5-10 years before). Many federal employees elect Option B early in their career when they have young children and a mortgage, then never revisit the decision. By retirement, circumstances have changed dramatically — kids are grown, the house is paid off, and the need for large life insurance coverage has diminished. Reviewing coverage every few years ensures you're not over-insured and overpaying for protection you no longer need.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script>
(function() {
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-trigger').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
      var item = this.closest('.fed-ed-faq-item');
      var isOpen = item.classList.contains('active');
      
      // Close all items
      document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-item').forEach(function(el) {
        el.classList.remove('active');
      });
      
      // Open clicked item if it wasn't already open
      if (!isOpen) {
        item.classList.add('active');
      }
    });
  });
  
  // Smooth scroll for navigation links
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-fegli-nav a').forEach(function(link) {
    link.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      const targetId = this.getAttribute('href');
      const targetElement = document.querySelector(targetId);
      if (targetElement) {
        targetElement.scrollIntoView({
          behavior: 'smooth',
          block: 'start'
        });
      }
    });
  });
})();
</script>